  "why": "Although the paper presents a novel data-augmentation approach that generates failure-inducing variants and measures improvements in robust accuracy, it does not analyze the discovered failures to diagnose underlying model weaknesses. There is no class-level or feature-level analysis of why the model fails on certain perturbations, no attribution of failures to dataset bias or spurious features, nor any deeper examination of neuron activation patterns or statistical failure clustering. The paper’s focus is solely on using worst-case variants to improve robustness, without providing diagnostic insights into model vulnerabilities.",
  "evidence": "• Section 4.3 (Page 1153): Evaluation metric is defined purely as robust accuracy (proportion of test inputs correctly classified under all perturbations), with no further analysis of failure modes.\n• Section 5 (Pages 1153–1156): Experimental results report aggregate robust accuracy improvements (Tables 2–5) and training time reductions, but contain no breakdown of failures by class, input pattern, or model internals that would explain root causes.\n• Section 3.3–3.4 (Pages 1150–1151): Describes fitness functions (loss-based, neuron-coverage) and selective augmentation criteria, yet these are used solely to drive augmentation decisions, not to analyze or diagnose model weaknesses."
